Copy of earlier post:  Proper testing may save a lot of un-needed work!



----- Original Message -----
From: "Volkswagen Restorations USA" <volksfix(-at-)bellsouth.net>
>
>     With the key "ON",  check the wire to the sending unit with a volt
> meter, (wire disconnected) you should have 10.0 to 10.5 volts with the key
> on. If the voltage is correct, ground the wire and the gauge should read
> "full".  This will check the wiring, voltage stabilizer, and gauge, if it
> shows "full", then only the sending unit is left to be the trouble!
>
> VOLTAGE INCORRECT:
>
>     If the voltage is "In-Correct", check the voltage Stabilizer behind
the
> speedometer, going into the gauge. You should have battery voltage
available
> (12.4 volts plus or minus) going in, and 10.5 coming out going into the
> gauge. If not replace the stabilizer and recheck.
>
> VOLTAGE CORRECT:
>
>     If the voltage going into the gauge is correct, and the gauge doesn't
> read "full", with the wire grounded, replace gauge, and recheck.
>
>     Sounds complicated but it isn't. The idea behind all this is, that if
> there is not a fixed voltage going into the gauge, it would "swing" as the
> available voltage changed. Such as at idle, high RPM's, or when you turned
> on a high voltage consumer, headlamps for instance.
>     Good luck.
>
> Tommy
> Volkswagen Restorations USA
> www.freeyellow.com/members7/volksfix1/
